While this project demonstrated the effectiveness of the Home-Based SOC Environment in detecting a wide range of cyber threats, several 
areas of improvement and future research could enhance its functionality and deployment in more complex environments.

1. Integration with SIEM Solutions

Future work could explore integrating the ELK Stack with other Security Information and Event Management (SIEM) systems for more advanced
log management and correlation. Solutions such as Splunk or Security Onion could further streamline threat analysis, incident response,
and the overall monitoring workflow.

2. Automated Threat Response

The integration of an Intrusion Prevention System (IPS) with the SOC could help provide automated mitigation of detected threats. By 
connecting the SOC environment to firewalls or other security mechanisms, the system could prevent attacks in real time rather than merely
detecting them.

3. Deployment in Larger Environments

Testing the home-based SOC in larger, production-level environments would provide insights into the system’s scalability and performance 
under higher data volumes and more complex attack scenarios. This would also help assess its potential for use in enterprise settings.

4. Expansion of Attack Scenarios

Future work could expand the range of simulated attack scenarios, including more advanced threats such as zero-day exploits, polymorphic
malware, and advanced persistent threats (APTs). This would help refine the detection rules and improve the SOC’s resilience against a
broader spectrum of cyber threats. By addressing these areas of improvement, future research and development can enhance the capabilities 
of home-based SOCs, making them more adaptable, scalable,and effective in real-world cybersecurity operations.
